🔍 3. Key Layers Explained
🧩 [1] VFS (Virtual File System)
Acts as a unified interface.

You call:

read("file.txt")
VFS decides:

Which filesystem? (ext4, xfs, nfs)

Which inode?

Key Data Structures:
super_block → filesystem metadata

inode → file metadata

dentry → directory cache

file → open file instance

👉 VFS = abstraction layer

📂 [2] Filesystem Layer (ext4 example)
Handles:

File layout

Block mapping

Metadata management

Example: ext4
Uses:

Inodes

Extent trees (efficient block mapping)

Mapping flow:
File offset → Logical block → Physical block
⚡ [3] Page Cache (VERY IMPORTANT)
RAM cache for file data

Avoids disk access

Read:
If present → cache hit

Else → fetch from disk

Write:
Data written to cache first

Marked dirty

Later flushed to disk (writeback)

🔁 [4] Block Layer
Responsible for:

Request merging

Scheduling

Queueing I/O

Converts:
Filesystem blocks → sectors
Example:
block size = 4KB
sector size = 512B

1 block = 8 sectors
⚙️ [5] Device Driver
Talks to actual hardware

Converts generic I/O → device-specific commands

💾 [6] Storage Device
Types:
HDD → mechanical, slow

SSD → flash-based

NVMe → ultra-fast, parallel queues

EBS → network-attached block storage

